## Introduction

- Extracellular deposition of fibrillar proteins
  - can lead to inflammation
- *General term *
- Different abnormal proteins can lead to amyloidosis
- Proteins can be due to misfolding
- Proteins attract deposition of sugars
  - these stain like starch (amyloid )
  - so named Amyloidosis

## Basic ideas to understand the pathogenesis

- Accumulation is **extracellular**
- Leads to **pressure atrophy** of nearby structures
  - Leads to local ischemia âž¡ cell death

## Appearance in H&E

- Amorphous
- Hyaline (glass like )
- Eosinophilic (pink)

- Other Hyaline substances

## Chemical nature

- 95% fibrillar proteins
- 5 % P component and glycoproteins (mostly sugar vs proteoglycans which are mostly protein ) see [[Amyloidosis#Diagnosis]]

### Most common proteins in Amyloid

#### ALL - Amyloid Light Chain

- Has the word light chain, so think immunoglobulin
- Specifically lambda light chain of Ig, kappa is also seen
- IgG source - plasma cells (differentiated B cells)
- So if you have a plasma cell tumour (multiple myeloma)
- You'll have amyloidosis

#### Amyloid Associated

- This is NOT from immunoglobulin
- Instead it's from the liver
- See this flow chart
- Since it's amyloidosis secondary to chronic inflammation
- It's called secondary amyloidosis

#### Beta Amyloid

- Source - proteolysis of Amyloid Precursor protein âž¡ Abeta Amyloid
- Involved Alzheimers (see CNS Path )

### Other sources for amyloid proteins

#### **Transthyretin**

- Normal plasma protein
- Transports vitamin A and Thyroxine
- Misfolded/mutated TTR - Genetic familial amyloidosis
- Normal TRR accumulation
- In hearts of aged
- Senile systemic amyloidosis

#### [[Amyloidosis#Hemodialysis Associated Amyloidosis]]

#### Prions

## Pathogenesis

![Pasted image 20210721191400.png](data:image/png;base64,)

- Just see this flowchart

- Protein accumulation extracellularly
  - Amyloidosis can be Local (Organ specific )
    - Systemic
    - Hereditary

- Study this table

- ![Pasted image 20210721191440.png](data:image/png;base64,)

- If amyloidosis due to *Immunoglobulin* accumulation
  - it's primary (read about multiple myeloma )

- If due to *chronic inflammation* it's secondary
  - Mediated by  SAA

- Normally SAA is degraded to soluble products by macrophages (why macrophage since it's chronic inflammation )
  - So for amyloidosis to occur either SAA is abnormal or isn't degraded due to an  enzyme deficiency

- ![Pasted image 20210721190159.png](data:image/png;base64,)

### Familial Hereditary Type

#### Familial Mediterranean fever

- Autoinflammatory condition
- Mediated by interleukin 1 (see [[inflammasome]] in chapter 3 )
- IL 1 = fever
- Also inflammation of serous surfaces (pleura, peritoneum )
- Same as chronic inflammation
- IL 1 âž¡ SAA âž¡ amyloidosis

#### Familial amyloidotic Polyneuropathy

- TTR mutation  (misfolded and resistant to proteolysis)
- So amyloidosis

> - Why are misfolded proteins resistant to proteolysis?

- Normal proteins in body have enzymes for degradation
- Misfolded proteins are seen as foreign, hence they lack enzymes

### Hemodialysis Associated Amyloidosis

- Hemodialysis for CRF
- Accumulation of **Beta 2 macro Globulin**
- seen in MHC 1
  - Macro globin is big, so it isn't filtered via dialysis
- Leads to clinical features of amyloidosis
- accumulates in joints 
- associated with CTS (Any amyloidosis can cause CTS)

### Localised Amyloidosis

- Seen in specific tissues under microscopy
- Protein is **AL**
- So it's due to a plasma cell tumour

### Endocrine Amyloidosis

- Seen in endocrine tumours (thyroid medullary , [[phaeochromocytoma]] )
- [[Type 2 diabetes]] (excess insulting secretion because body is insensitive to insulin, higher conc is secreted )
- Source of Amyloid in DM **amylin** released along with insulin and c peptide
- Endocrine tumours - hormone polypeptide

### Amyloidosis in Aging

- Seen in 70+ age ground
- Affects heart
  - Senile cardiac amyloidosis
- Amyloid protein = **normal TTR**

## Morphology / Clinical features

- Organ affected âž¡ clinical features
  - Initially Organ looks big
  - Then due to Amyloid accumulation (not hypertrophy or hyperplasia)
    - The Organ shrinks due to pressure atrophy (see types of atrophy in chapter 2 )

### **Kidney**
  - most common organ involved
  - Mostly in glomerulus
  - But can also affect the vasculature
  - Leads to capillary stenosis due to Amyloid
  - > Leads to [[Nephrotic syndrome]]
so you will have edema
![Pasted image 20210721193000.png](data:image/png;base64,)

### **Spleen**

- Spleenomgealy
  - **Sago spleen **
    - Accumulation in spleenic follicles
    - white pulp (splenic lymphoid follicles)
    - Looks like sago (dot dot dot stuff )
  - **Lardaceous Spleen **
  - red pulp (venous sinuses with RBCs)
  - waxy Appearance
    - Accumulation in Walls of spleenic  sinuses and connective tissue framework

### **Liver**

- Hepatomegaly
  - Amyloidosis seen
  - But liver function is preserved
Congo red stained liver 
![Pasted image 20210721192858.png](data:image/png;base64,)
Under Polarising Microscope
![Pasted image 20210721192949.png](data:image/png;base64,)

### **Heart**
  - Mc in Senile amyloidosis
  - Presents as sudden cardiac failure
    - Can lead to *arrhythmia* due to disruption of conduction system
    - Or restrictive [[cardiomyopathy]]

### Other locations
  - Tongue - leads to macroglossia
    - > Impairs speech ,swallowing

- cerebral vessels involvement in  Alzheimer's (Abeta)

- Blood vessels
  - Increased tendency to bleed / rupture

- Forearm
  - associated with [[Amyloidosis#Hemodialysis Associated Amyloidosis]]
  - Carpal ligament
  - > Compression syndrome  âž¡ [[carpal tunnel syndrome]]

## Diagnosis

- > Amyloid in ME is essential
- Mc site to biopsy - Abdominal fat 
  - if negative biopsy suspected tissue  (eg kidney )
- Electrophoresis M band if amyloidosis due to [[Amyloidosis#ALL - Amyloid Light Chain]]
- Amyloid protein can found by using immunohistochemical staining (antibody specific to a protein)
- Nuclear imaging
  - Serum amyloid P component (SAP) scintigraphy has high sensitivity for detecting amyloid in multiple organ sites.
  - SAP has a high affinity for amyloid.
---
## Prognosis

- Generalised amyloidosis - poor
- AL amyloidosis - 2 yrs, lower if associated with multiple myeloma
- If due to chronic disease
  - treatment of the chronic disease can help
  - you might think since the accumulation is extracellular 
  - remove Amyloid via surgery 
  - but you can't remove Amyloid from affected tissues 
  - Organ transplantation can help though
